docs.abstract: An uncommonly strong debut from the Vietnamese director Pham Thien An asks existential questions without answers.
docs.snippet: An uncommonly strong debut from the Vietnamese director Pham Thien An asks existential questions without answers.
docs.lead_paragraph: The complex dance of doubt and religious faith is frequently cast in terms of a quest. One might be “on a faith journey,” or be “a lost soul,” or be “searching” for meaning and the divine — all images derived from the idea of starting at one place, keeping your eyes open, and ending up, ultimately, in some final destination. Small wonder that many human cultures imagine a wander in the wilderness, literal or metaphorical, as pivotal to one’s initiation into maturity. Some fresh wisdom and revelation comes from walking around in circles for a while.

headline.main: ‘Inside the Yellow Cocoon Shell’ Review: A Wanderer on a Spiritual Quest
headline.print_headline: Searching for God But Finding Frustration

docs.abstract: A playlist honoring David Crosby, Wayne Shorter, Sinead O’Connor, Jimmy Buffett and other musicians who died this year.
docs.snippet: A playlist honoring David Crosby, Wayne Shorter, Sinead O’Connor, Jimmy Buffett and other musicians who died this year.
docs.lead_paragraph: Doesn’t it seem like the “In Memoriam” segments on awards shows get longer with each passing year? It can sometimes feel like we’re in a perpetual state of mourning, saying goodbye to one brilliant musician after the next. Social media, the 24-hour news cycle and an aging population of era-defining artists all contribute to the perception that we’re constantly suffering huge losses.

docs.abstract: This documentary is both a look at a small, obsessive film club that formed in the early ’90s in South Korea and an origin story of the director Bong Joon Ho, who was in the group.
docs.snippet: This documentary is both a look at a small, obsessive film club that formed in the early ’90s in South Korea and an origin story of the director Bong Joon Ho, who was in the group.
docs.lead_paragraph: Every filmmaker, including the great ones, starts somewhere — even if that means making a low-rent stop-motion short called “Looking for Paradise” that’s about a stuffed gorilla searching for freedom while fighting a caterpillar that emerged from its fecal matter. That was how a young, student Bong Joon Ho made his debut, a saga detailed in “Yellow Door: ’90s Lo-Fi Film Club,” a charming documentary about a cohort of South Korean cinephiles formed in 1992.

headline.main: ‘Yellow Door: ’90s Lo-Fi Film Club’ Review: Cinema Education

docs.abstract: DURING the Meadowlands Grand Prix today, Dr. Dave Crippen, tall and lean in his hooded white fireproof suit, will be sitting in a yellow truck at Turn 4 on the 1.68-mile road circuit that winds through the Sports Complex like an asphalt serpent. As he sits there watching the Indianapolis-type cars roar by, he will be listening for words he doesn't want to hear.   ''I take my eye off the track every so often,'' he was saying now, ''but I never take my ear off the radio.''   The words Dave Crippen doesn't want to hear on the radio are, ''Yellow, yellow, yellow - heavy contact at . . .'' On the radio the voice then would report where the crash, or ''heavy contact,'' had occurred, say at Turn 6, then the voice would identify whether the crash at the wall had happened on the driver's side or the right side.
